dismissalText.commentary: Kusal Perera run out (Anwar Ali/Mohammad Irfan) 116 (109b 9x4 4x6 157m) SR: 106.42

dismissalComment.html: another run-out. The only way they seem to be able to get wickets today. Perera is out for 116. This is played towards long leg, they decide to come back for the second, but the throw comes to Perera's end, and is accurate. Perera, who has recently been hit on the toe. Irfan collects it, and while he has broken the wicket with his arm, it is still considered a part of the hand as long as the ball is in his hand. Perera was not the most urgent while taking the first. And yet again, it is Anwar Ali doing wonders in the outfield

dismissalText.commentary: Tillakaratne Dilshan run out (Ahmed Shehzad) 62 (70b 6x4 0x6 111m) SR: 88.57

dismissalComment.html: Dilshan has stolen quite a few singles today but he has picked the wrong man this time. Short of a length, just outside off, dropped at his feet, towards cover, charges through for one, Ahmed Shehzad swoops in on it, and throws the stumps at the non-striker's end down. Dilshan is caught well short

dismissalText.commentary: Mohammad Hafeez lbw b Mathews 37 (37b 5x4 1x6 46m) SR: 100

dismissalComment.html: that's No. 100 for Mathews. not yet. Wait on. Hafeez has reviewed this lbw decision. Mathews bowls on a length, this nips back in front just outside off. Beats the inside edge, and hits him in front of middle and leg. There is no bat6 involved. It looks like going down leg, but since the umpire has given it, all the ball has to do is clip the leg stump. And clip it it does. Mathews gets his 100th, and what a big wicket it is too. Hafeez walks back shaking his head

dismissalText.commentary: Azhar Ali run out (Mathews) 35 (42b 5x4 0x6 57m) SR: 83.33

dismissalComment.html: suicidal single. Pushed firmly and straight to mid-off, and he just sets off hoping there will be a misfield or an off-target throw. Mathews, though, hits the base of the stumps. Pressure showing on Pakistan

Chandimal has stumped him. Or has he? Senanayake has got a wicket in his first over. Shehzad makes room to try to hit this over mid-off. The ball pitches on off, and keeps on going with the angle. Shehzad tries to slide back, but he is caught on the line. It's a tight call, but no part of the foot is behind the line

dismissalText.commentary: Sarfaraz Ahmed run out (Lakmal) 27 (24b 3x4 0x6 38m) SR: 112.5

dismissalComment.html: lovely direct hit from third man. Lakmal is the man. They have taken two couples to his right already this over, and once again Sarfraz places it straight of that man. This time he cuts the angle, gets to the ball quicker, and lets rip a direct hit on the half-volley. Sarfraz is stunned, and caught short. Lovely replay. Ian Gould, the square leg umpire, enjoyed that piece of fielding

commentPostTextItems.html: And with that we leave you as Pakistan players get their hands onto the trophy. Thanks for joining us through the tour. Don't forget there are two T20s too. Goodbye

"We wanted to win this game," says Azhar Ali. "but credit goes to Sri Lanka. They played really well. We didn't bowl that well, but the credit should go to the Sri Lankan batsmen, especially the way they batted in the first half. Unfortunately we didn't win today, but happy with the series win. We played positive cricket, especially as a batting unit. The fielding was exceptional. After a long time you saw brilliance in the field. Credit should be given to the coaching staff."

"Really happy to get this," says Mohammad Hafeez, the Man of the Series. "But the whole team deserves this award. We got worked hard for the series, and thankfully the results went our way. I am trying my best to contribute to the victory of Pakistan."

"Unfortunately a bit too late but a clinical performance," says Angelo Mathews. "Openers were brilliant, then Thirimanne and Chandimal. They gave us the platform for myself, and Milinda was a pleasure to watch. We had to go back to our basics, especially in the bowling department. We showed a bit of improvement in the fielding. You need to keep improving day by day."

"The team needed that innings," says Kusal Perera, the Man of the Match. "We had already lost the series, but 3-2 is better than 4-1. Yeah team-mates reminded me of a possible double, but I am happy the team won. I am always trying to get my basics right. I know if my basics are right, the results will go my way."

9.51pm That's a comprehensive consolation victory for Sri Lanka after Pakistan took the series-winning lead of 3-1 in Colombo. Dilshan walks off with a stump. He became only the 11th man to score 10000 ODI runs. He played a big part in setting up this win, but it was Kusal Perera who took the game away from Paksitan ins coring his second ODI hundred. And he did so while avoiding his trademark low-percentage game. He waited for balls he could hit, and boy did he hit them, for nine fours and a six in his 109-ball 116. The middle order was stable with a couple of 29s, and then Angelo Mathews and Milinda Siriwardana provided a grand finish with explosive fifties. Pakistan needed a miracle to chase down 369. Tonight was not the night for miracles. Sachithra Senanayake will be happy with his comeback figures of 8-1-39-3. Thisara Perera will feel some relief with 8-0-38-2. Pakistan, though, win the series and still remain ahead of West Indies in the ODI rankings, which means they should qualify for the Champions Trophy if there is no more ODI cricket until September 30. We will get the presentation soon

commentTextItems.html: flat length ball, Rahat stays back to defend
another bouncer, following Irfan again, and this time he bottom-edges it towards the keeper
Irfan gies him the charge, Gamage bowls a fullie that is headed towards top of off, but Irfan just gets a touch of the bat
he has slugged this powerfully. Four bouncers followed by a short ball, and he clears the front leg to crash this through midwicket
a bouncer that follows Irfan, and beats the hook for a dot ball
another no-ball. Irfan makes room and swings, but fails to connect with the short ball. Gamage has overstepped again
a third no-ball from Gamage as he looks to bounce Irfan. Beats him on the hook but a free hit is coming up

dismissalText.commentary: Tillakaratne Dilshan run out (Ahmed Shehzad) 62 (70b 6x4 0x6 111m) SR: 88.57

dismissalComment.html: Dilshan has stolen quite a few singles today but he has picked the wrong man this time. Short of a length, just outside off, dropped at his feet, towards cover, charges through for one, Ahmed Shehzad swoops in on it, and throws the stumps at the non-striker's end down. Dilshan is caught well short

dismissalText.commentary: Kusal Perera run out (Anwar Ali/Mohammad Irfan) 116 (109b 9x4 4x6 157m) SR: 106.42

dismissalComment.html: another run-out. The only way they seem to be able to get wickets today. Perera is out for 116. This is played towards long leg, they decide to come back for the second, but the throw comes to Perera's end, and is accurate. Perera, who has recently been hit on the toe. Irfan collects it, and while he has broken the wicket with his arm, it is still considered a part of the hand as long as the ball is in his hand. Perera was not the most urgent while taking the first. And yet again, it is Anwar Ali doing wonders in the outfield

dismissalText.commentary: Lahiru Thirimanne c Mohammad Rizwan b Rahat Ali 30 (30b 2x4 0x6 57m) SR: 100

dismissalComment.html: and he provides Pakistan some relief. This is a full and wide delivery, Thirimanne looks to squeeze this past point with an open face, but ends up hitting it straight to the man

dismissalText.commentary: Dinesh Chandimal c Sarfaraz Ahmed b Rahat Ali 29 (25b 3x4 1x6 34m) SR: 116

dismissalComment.html: Rahat gets another wicket. Slower ball this time. Chandimal sees one short of a length and looks to open the face, but this cutter deceives him and he is early into the shot. The edge settles with Sarfraz who dives forward

dismissalText.commentary: Azhar Ali run out (Mathews) 35 (42b 5x4 0x6 57m) SR: 83.33

dismissalComment.html: suicidal single. Pushed firmly and straight to mid-off, and he just sets off hoping there will be a misfield or an off-target throw. Mathews, though, hits the base of the stumps. Pressure showing on Pakistan

headshotImage.caption: Dinesh Chandimal, player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Dinesh Chandimal, player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Ahmed Shehzad st Chandimal b Senanayake 18 (23b 2x4 0x6 43m) SR: 78.26

dismissalComment.html: Chandimal has stumped him. Or has he? Senanayake has got a wicket in his first over. Shehzad makes room to try to hit this over mid-off. The ball pitches on off, and keeps on going with the angle. Shehzad tries to slide back, but he is caught on the line. It's a tight call, but no part of the foot is behind the line

headshotImage.caption: Angelo Mathews, player page headshot cutout 2023
headshotImage.longCaption: Angelo Mathews, player page headshot cutout 2023

dismissalText.commentary: Mohammad Hafeez lbw b Mathews 37 (37b 5x4 1x6 46m) SR: 100

dismissalComment.html: that's No. 100 for Mathews. not yet. Wait on. Hafeez has reviewed this lbw decision. Mathews bowls on a length, this nips back in front just outside off. Beats the inside edge, and hits him in front of middle and leg. There is no bat6 involved. It looks like going down leg, but since the umpire has given it, all the ball has to do is clip the leg stump. And clip it it does. Mathews gets his 100th, and what a big wicket it is too. Hafeez walks back shaking his head

headshotImage.caption: Suranga Lakmal, player page headshot cutout 2022
headshotImage.longCaption: Suranga Lakmal, player page headshot cutout 2022

dismissalText.commentary: Sarfaraz Ahmed run out (Lakmal) 27 (24b 3x4 0x6 38m) SR: 112.5

dismissalComment.html: lovely direct hit from third man. Lakmal is the man. They have taken two couples to his right already this over, and once again Sarfraz places it straight of that man. This time he cuts the angle, gets to the ball quicker, and lets rip a direct hit on the half-volley. Sarfraz is stunned, and caught short. Lovely replay. Ian Gould, the square leg umpire, enjoyed that piece of fielding

dismissalText.commentary: Shoaib Malik c Thirimanne b NLTC Perera 11 (10b 1x4 0x6 21m) SR: 110

dismissalComment.html: Perera gets his wicket at his favourite ground. It's Malik who is out. Maybe he doesn;t like the dog. Just charges at a length ball, but is not close enough to the pitch of the ball. Ends up dragging it, and short midwicket takes the catch off the inside half of the bat

dismissalText.commentary: Mohammad Rizwan c Chandimal b NLTC Perera 29 (34b 4x4 0x6 50m) SR: 85.29

dismissalComment.html: Perera gets another on his favourite ground, and this is the specialist batsman, Rizwan. Perera bowls short of a length, on top of off, Rizwan goes back and looks to open the face, but manages just an edge through to Chandimal

dismissalText.commentary: Imad Wasim c & b Senanayake 15 (17b 2x4 0x6 23m) SR: 88.23

dismissalComment.html: Senanayake had him last over, but he gets Wasim out again. This is just a gentle offbreak, Wasim is not close to the pitch of it just outside off, and plays in front of his body. Lofts it to the right of Senanayake who dives full length to take the catch

headshotImage.longCaption: Anwar Ali player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Anwar Ali c NLTC Perera b Gamage 11 (14b 2x4 0x6 26m) SR: 78.57

dismissalComment.html: and now Sri Lanka are one wicket short. Gamage gets his first wicket of the night. This is short, pretty straight, and cramps him up as Anwar looks for a big shot. Can't get any power into the shot, and he just mis-hits it for a dolly to mid-on

dismissalText.commentary: Yasir Shah c NLTC Perera b Senanayake 9 (13b 1x4 0x6 11m) SR: 69.23

dismissalComment.html: Shah falls for 9. The first man out of the 15 that have batted today to not reach double figures. Senanayake flights one, Shah sees a big hit, jumps out of the crease, gets a thick edge for an overhead catch at short cover

headshotImage.caption: Milinda Siriwardana player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Milinda Siriwardana player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Rahat Ali c Senanayake b Siriwardana 0 (7b 0x4 0x6 11m) SR: 0

dismissalComment.html: and Siriwardana gets a wicket to end the match. Flighted on off, Rahat looks for the bog hit, but all he manages is an aerial hit straight to long-off where Senanayake takes the catch

recentReportStory.title: Kusal ton sets up consolation SL victory
recentReportStory.subTitle: Sri Lanka v Pakistan, 5th ODI, Hambantota
recentReportStory.seoTitle: Kusal ton sets up consolation SL victory
recentReportStory.summary: Kusal Perera sent Pakistan on the run with his most substantial, and perhaps most mature, innings to date, then Sri Lanka's middle order ran the opposition down and mauled them in a frenzied finish, to found a 165-run victory in the final ODI
recentReportStory.byline: The Report by Andrew Fidel Fernando
